body:
this definately appears to be a revert issue. This change allows the standard slim problem handler to work:

```
protected function renderHtmlException($exception)
    {
        $title = 'Slim Application Error';
//more exciting code
```

OK, this is a relatively minimal example:

In routes:

```
//for orders and related systems
$app->group('/order', function() {
    $this->get('/errorHandleTest', function($request, $response, $args) {
        $pdo = $this->ro_db;
        $orderId = 'UT025SON60.66';

        $baseDataQuery = $pdo->prepare('
            SELECT o.*
            FROM orders AS o
            WHERE o.orders_id = :orderId
        ');
        $baseDataQuery->execute([':orderId' => $orderId]);
        $baseData = $baseDataQuery->fetch(); //using Assoc fetch mode - this makes sense in the full version

        $order = \Models\Slim\OrderTest::loadFromRow($baseData, $pdo);
        $response->write('page');
        return $response;

    });

});
```

In the fetched Model:

```

<?php
namespace Models\Slim;


class OrderTest
{
    private $id;

    public function getId() {
        return $this->id;
    }

    public function setId($id) {
        $this->id = $id;
        return $this;
    }

    public function addItem($item) {
        return true;
    }

    public function initialise($pdo) {

        $orderItemsQuery = $pdo->prepare('
            SELECT * FROM orders_items
            WHERE orders_id = :orderId
        ');
        $orderItemsQuery->setFetchMode(\PDO::FETCH_CLASS, '\Models\Slim\OrderItemTest');
        $orderItemsQuery->execute([':orderId' => $this->getId()]);
        $this->addItem($orderItemsQuery->fetchAll());

        return $this;
    }


    public static function loadFromRow($row, $pdo)
    {
        $order = new OrderTest();
        $order->setId($row['orders_id']);

        $order->initialise($pdo);
        return $order;
    }


}

class OrderItemTest {

    public function __construct()
    {
        parent::__construct(); //deliberate error
    }

}


```

This all basically fetches a row and drops it into a class and then runs an additional query to populate some objects our old model (which is being extended in the real version), which it requires to function. For some reason I couldn't replicate the effect by causing the error in the OrderTest constructor.

I've run out of time to remove the PDO, I'll strip it out if you need me to (although I suspect the PDO is fundamentally the cause).

$app->get('/test', function ($request, $response, $args) {
    try {
        //Trigger a PHP error - Exceptions since PHP 7, but not a subclass of \Exception, which is the issue
        $myClass = new NonExistantClass();
    } catch (Throwable $ex) {
        throw new Exception("Some new exception wrapping this one", 0, $ex);
    }
});
